[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] In number theory, a **cusp form** is a particular kind of modular form with zero constant coefficient in its Fourier series expansion.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] For other groups, there may be some translation through several units, in which case the Fourier expansion is in terms of a different parameter.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] In all cases, though, the limit as *q* → 0 is the limit in the upper half-plane as the imaginary part of *z* → ∞.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] Taking the quotient by the modular group, this limit corresponds to a cusp of a modular curve (in the sense of a point added for compactification).
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] So, the definition amounts to saying that a cusp form is a modular form that vanishes at a cusp.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] In the case of other groups, there may be several cusps, and the definition becomes a modular form vanishing at *all* cusps.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] The dimensions of spaces of cusp forms are, in principle, computable via the Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] For example, the Ramanujan tau function *τ*(*n*) arises as the sequence of Fourier coefficients of the cusp form of weight 12 for the modular group, with *a*1 = 1.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] The space of such forms has dimension 1, which means this definition is possible; and that accounts for the action of Hecke operators on the space being by scalar multiplication (Mordell's proof of Ramanujan's identities).
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] which represents (up to a normalizing constant) the discriminant of the cubic on the right side of the Weierstrass equation of an elliptic curve; and the 24-th power of the Dedekind eta function.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] The Fourier coefficients here are written $\tau (n)$ and called 'Ramanujan's tau function', with the normalization *τ*(1) = 1.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] More generally, the integral remains finite if f is a cusp form and g is a modular form, both of weight k .
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] With respect to this inner product, there is an orthogonal decomposition $M_{k}(\Gamma )=E_{k}(\Gamma )\oplus S_{k}(\Gamma )$ where $M_{k}(\Gamma )$ is the space of modular forms, $S_{k}(\Gamma )$ the space of cusp forms, and $E_{k}(\Gamma )$ is the space of Eisenstein series, all of weight k .
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] In the larger picture of automorphic forms, the cusp forms are complementary to Eisenstein series, in a *discrete spectrum*/*continuous spectrum*, or *discrete series representation*/*induced representation* distinction typical in different parts of spectral theory.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] That is, Eisenstein series can be 'designed' to take on given values at cusps.
[src:modular-forms/cusp-form] There is a large general theory, depending though on the quite intricate theory of parabolic subgroups, and corresponding cuspidal representations.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] In mathematics, **Eisenstein series**, named after German mathematician Gotthold Eisenstein, are particular modular forms with infinite series expansions that may be written down directly.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Originally defined for the modular group, Eisenstein series can be generalized in the theory of automorphic forms.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Let $\tau$ be a complex number with strictly positive imaginary part.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] This series absolutely converges to a holomorphic function of $\tau$ in the upper half-plane and its Fourier expansion given below shows that it extends to a holomorphic function at $\tau =i\infty$ .
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] It is a remarkable fact that the Eisenstein series is a modular form.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Indeed, the key property is its $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ -invariance.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Note that it is important to assume that $k\geq 2$ to ensure absolute convergence of the series, as otherwise it would be illegitimate to change the order of summation in the proof of $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ -invariance.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] In fact, there are no nontrivial modular forms of weight 2.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Nevertheless, an analogue of the holomorphic Eisenstein series can be defined even for $k=1$ , although it would only be a quasimodular form.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] It is also necessary that the weight be even, as otherwise the sum vanishes because the $(-m,-n)$ and $(m,n)$ terms cancel each other.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] The article on modular invariants provides expressions for these two functions in terms of theta functions.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Any holomorphic modular form for the modular group can be written as a polynomial in $G_{4}$ and $G_{6}$ .
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Specifically, the higher order $G_{2k}$ can be written in terms of $G_{4}$ and $G_{6}$ through a recurrence relation.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] where $B_{n}$ are the Bernoulli numbers, $\zeta$ is the Riemann zeta function and $\sigma _{p}(n)$ is the divisor sum function, i.e. the sum of the p -th powers of the divisors of n .
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] where $\theta _{m}$ and $\vartheta _{ij}$ are alternative notations.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Eisenstein series form the most explicit examples of modular forms for the full modular group $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Since the space of modular forms of weight $2k$ has dimension 1 for $2k=4,6,8,10,14$ , different products of Eisenstein series having those weights have to be equal up to a scalar multiple.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] for the number $r_{\Gamma }(n)$ of vectors of the squared length $2n$ in the root lattice of the type *E*8.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Similar techniques involving holomorphic Eisenstein series twisted by a Dirichlet character produce formulas for the number of representations of a positive integer n ' as a sum of two, four, or eight squares in terms of the divisors of n .
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Using the above recurrence relation, all higher $E_{2k}$ can be expressed as polynomials in $E_{4}$ and $E_{6}$ .
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Srinivasa Ramanujan gave several interesting identities between the first few Eisenstein series involving differentiation.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] These identities, like the identities between the series, yield arithmetical convolution identities involving the sum-of-divisor function.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Automorphic forms generalize the idea of modular forms for general semisimple Lie groups, where the modular group is replaced by an arithmetic group.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] Robert Langlands generalised the theory of Eisenstein series to this setting.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] When the Lie group is of type A1 the theory resembles the classical case.
[src:modular-forms/eisenstein-series] For example, Hilbert modular forms are well-studied.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] In mathematics, in particular in the theory of modular forms, a **Hecke operator**, studied by Erich Hecke (1937a,1937b), is a certain kind of "averaging" operator that plays a significant role in the structure of vector spaces of modular forms and more general automorphic representations.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Hecke operators can be realized in a number of contexts.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] with the sum taken over all the ${\textstyle \Lambda '}$ that are subgroups of ${\textstyle \Lambda }$ of index n .
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] For example, with ${\textstyle n=2}$ and two dimensions, there are three such ${\textstyle \Lambda '}$ .
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Another way to express Hecke operators is by means of double cosets in the modular group.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] In the contemporary adelic approach, this translates to double cosets with respect to some compact subgroups.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Let ${\textstyle M_{m}}$ be the set of ${\textstyle 2\times 2}$ integral matrices with determinant m and ${\textstyle \Gamma =M_{1}}$ be the full modular group ${\textstyle {\text{SL}}_{2}(\mathbb {Z} )}$ .
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] where ${\textstyle z}$ is in the upper half-plane and the normalization constant ${\textstyle m^{k-1}}$ assures that the image of a form with integer Fourier coefficients has integer Fourier coefficients.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] One can see from this explicit formula that Hecke operators with different indices commute and that if ${\textstyle a(0)=0}$ then ${\textstyle b(0)=0}$ , so the subspace ${\textstyle S_{k}}$ of cusp forms of weight k is preserved by the Hecke operators.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] If a (non-zero) cusp form f is a simultaneous eigenform of all Hecke operators ${\textstyle T_{m}}$ with eigenvalues ${\textstyle \lambda _{m}}$ then ${\textstyle a(m)=\lambda _{m}a(1)}$ and ${\textstyle a(1)\neq 1}$ .
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Thus for normalized cuspidal Hecke eigenforms of integer weight, their Fourier coefficients coincide with their Hecke eigenvalues.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Mordell (1917) used Hecke operators on modular forms in a paper on the special cusp form of Ramanujan, ahead of the general theory given by Hecke (1937a,1937b).
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Mordell proved the Hecke relations for the Ramanujan tau function, which implies that it is a multiplicative function, a property conjectured by Ramanujan.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] The idea goes back to earlier work of Adolf Hurwitz, who treated algebraic correspondences between modular curves which realise some individual Hecke operators.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Algebras of Hecke operators are called "Hecke algebras", and are commutative rings.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] In the classical elliptic modular form theory, the Hecke operators ${\textstyle T_{n}}$ with ${\textstyle n}$ coprime to the level acting on the space of cusp forms of a given weight are self-adjoint with respect to the Petersson inner product.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Therefore, the spectral theorem implies that there is a basis of modular forms that are eigenfunctions for these Hecke operators.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Each of these basic forms possesses an Euler product.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] More precisely, its Mellin transform is the Dirichlet series that has Euler products with the local factor for each prime ${\textstyle p}$ is the inverse of the **Hecke polynomial**, a quadratic polynomial in ${\textstyle p^{-s}}$ .
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] In the case treated by Mordell, the space of cusp forms of weight 12 with respect to the full modular group is one-dimensional.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] It follows that the Ramanujan form has an Euler product and establishes the multiplicativity of Ramanujan's tau function ${\textstyle \tau (n)}$ .
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] Other related mathematical rings are also called "Hecke algebras", although sometimes the link to Hecke operators is not entirely obvious.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] These algebras include certain quotients of the group algebras of braid groups.
[src:modular-forms/hecke-operator] The presence of this commutative operator algebra plays a significant role in the harmonic analysis of modular forms and generalisations.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In number theory and complex analysis, a **modular form** is a type of function of a complex number variable that possesses a high degree of symmetry, of a certain kind.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Similarly to a periodic function of a real variable, a modular form repeats or transforms in a certain way when its argument is subjected to a particular transformation.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Modular forms serve as an important bridge between complex analysis, number theory, and geometry.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Modular forms also appear in other areas, such as algebraic topology, sphere packing, and string theory.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] More precisely, a modular form is a holomorphic function on the complex upper half-plane that roughly satisfies a functional equation with respect to the group action of the modular group and a growth condition.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] A modular form is a special case of an automorphic form, which are functions defined on Lie groups that transform nicely with respect to the action of certain discrete subgroups, generalizing the example of the modular group $\mathrm {SL} _{2}(\mathbb {Z} )\subset \mathrm {SL} _{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The term *modular form*, as a systematic description, is usually attributed to Erich Hecke.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] identified with the function ${\textstyle \gamma (z)=(az+b)/(cz+d)}$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The identification of functions with matrices makes function composition equivalent to matrix multiplication.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] 3. f is bounded as $\operatorname {Im} (z)\to \infty$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] , the second condition above is equivalent to these two equations.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] If α is a non-zero complex number and *α*Λ is the lattice obtained by multiplying each element of Λ by α, then *F*(*α*Λ) = *α*−*k**F*(Λ) where k is a constant (typically a positive integer) called the **weight** of the form.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The absolute value of *F*(Λ) remains bounded above as long as the absolute value of the smallest non-zero element in Λ is bounded away from 0.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The key idea in proving the equivalence of the two definitions is that such a function F is determined, because of the second condition, by its values on lattices of the form **Z** + **Z***τ*, where *τ* ∈ **H**.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The simplest examples from this point of view are the Eisenstein series.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The condition *k* > 2 is needed for convergence; for odd k there is cancellation between *λ*−*k* and (−*λ*)−*k*, so that such series are identically zero.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] An even unimodular lattice L in **R***n* is a lattice generated by n vectors forming the columns of a matrix of determinant 1 and satisfying the condition that the square of the length of each vector in L is an even integer.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] converges when Im(z) > 0, and as a consequence of the Poisson summation formula can be shown to be a modular form of weight *n*/2.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] It is not so easy to construct even unimodular lattices, but here is one way: Let n be an integer divisible by 8 and consider all vectors v in **R***n* such that 2*v* has integer coordinates, either all even or all odd, and such that the sum of the coordinates of v is an even integer.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] When *n* = 8, this is the lattice generated by the roots in the root system called E8.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] even though the lattices *L*8 × *L*8 and *L*16 are not similar.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The presence of 24 is related to the fact that the Leech lattice has 24 dimensions.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] A celebrated conjecture of Ramanujan asserted that when Δ(*z*) is expanded as a power series in q, the coefficient of qp for any prime p has absolute value ≤ 2*p*11/2.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] This was confirmed by the work of Eichler, Shimura, Kuga, Ihara, and Pierre Deligne as a result of Deligne's proof of the Weil conjectures, which were shown to imply Ramanujan's conjecture.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The second and third examples give some hint of the connection between modular forms and classical questions in number theory, such as representation of integers by quadratic forms and the partition function.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The crucial conceptual link between modular forms and number theory is furnished by the theory of Hecke operators, which also gives the link between the theory of modular forms and representation theory.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] A modular function is a function that is invariant with respect to the modular group, but without the condition that it be holomorphic in the upper half-plane (among other requirements).
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Instead, a modular function for a finite-index subgroup $\Gamma$ of the modular group is a meromorphic function on the upper half-plane that is invariant under the action of $\Gamma$ and is meromorphic at the cusps.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Equivalently, it is a meromorphic function on the compactified modular curve associated with $\Gamma$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For the full modular group, a modular function is invariant under the transformations of the modular group and has a meromorphic expansion at the cusp $i\infty$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In terms of $q=\exp(2\pi iz)$ , this means that its *q*-expansion has only finitely many negative-power terms.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] When the weight *k* is zero, it can be shown using Liouville's theorem that the only modular forms are constant functions.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] However, relaxing the requirement that *f* be holomorphic leads to the notion of *modular functions*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] This is also referred to as the *q*-expansion of *f*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The coefficients $a_{n}$ are known as the Fourier coefficients of *f*, and the number *m* is called the order of the pole of *f*‍ at *i*∞.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] This condition is called "meromorphic at the cusp", meaning that only finitely many negative-*n* coefficients are non-zero, so the *q*-expansion is bounded below, guaranteeing that it is meromorphic at *q* = 0.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For subgroups of finite index, the same idea is expressed by requiring meromorphicity at each cusp of the subgroup.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] This condition allows the function to be regarded as meromorphic on the corresponding compactified modular curve.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Another way to phrase the definition of modular functions is to use elliptic curves: every lattice Λ determines an elliptic curve **C**/Λ over **C**; two lattices determine isomorphic elliptic curves if and only if one is obtained from the other by multiplying by some non-zero complex number α.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Thus, a modular function can also be regarded as a meromorphic function on the set of isomorphism classes of elliptic curves.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For example, the j-invariant *j*(*z*) of an elliptic curve, regarded as a function on the set of all elliptic curves, is a modular function.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] More concep­tually, modular functions can be thought of as functions on the moduli space of isomorphism classes of complex elliptic curves.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For the full modular group, a modular form *f*‍ that vanishes at *q* = 0 (equivalently, *a*0 = 0, also paraphrased as *z* = *i*∞) is called a *cusp form* (*Spitzenform* in German).
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For a finite-index subgroup of the modular group, a cusp form is a modular form that vanishes at every cusp of the subgroup.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] A *modular unit* is a modular function whose poles and zeroes are confined to the cusps.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The functional equation, i.e., the behavior of *f* with respect to $z\mapsto {\frac {az+b}{cz+d}}$ can be relaxed by requiring it only for matrices in smaller groups.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] A modular form for G of weight *k* is a function on **H** satisfying the above functional equation for all matrices in G, that is holomorphic on **H** and at all cusps of G.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Again, modular forms that vanish at all cusps are called cusp forms for G.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The **C**-vector spaces of modular and cusp forms of weight *k* are denoted *Mk*(*G*) and *Sk*(*G*), respectively.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Similarly, a meromorphic function on *G*\**H**∗ is called a modular function for G.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In case *G* = Γ0(*N*), they are also referred to as modular/cusp forms and functions of *level* *N*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For *G* = Γ(1) = SL(2, **Z**), this gives back the afore-mentioned definitions.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Let G be a subgroup of SL(2, **Z**) that is of finite index.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Such a group G acts on **H** in the same way as SL(2, **Z**).
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The quotient topological space *G*\**H** can be shown to be a Hausdorff space.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Typically it is not compact, but can be compactified by adding a finite number of points called *cusps*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] These are points at the boundary of **H**, i.e. in **Q**∪{∞}, such that there is a parabolic element of G (a matrix with trace ±2) fixing the point.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] This yields a compact topological space *G*\**H**∗.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] What is more, it can be endowed with the structure of a Riemann surface, which allows one to speak of holo- and meromorphic functions.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The geometry of *G*\**H**∗ can be understood by studying fundamental domains for *G*, i.e. subsets *D* ⊂ **H** such that *D* intersects each orbit of the G-action on **H** exactly once and such that the closure of *D* meets all orbits.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For example, the genus of *G*\**H**∗ can be computed.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The theory of Riemann surfaces can be applied to *G*\**H**∗ to obtain further information about modular forms and functions.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For example, the spaces *Mk*(*G*) and *Sk*(*G*) are finite-dimensional, and their dimensions can be computed thanks to the Riemann–Roch theorem in terms of the geometry of the G-action on **H**.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] where $\lfloor \cdot \rfloor$ denotes the floor function and k is even.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The modular functions constitute the field of functions of the Riemann surface, and hence form a field of transcendence degree one (over **C**).
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] If a modular function *f* is not identically 0, then it can be shown that the number of zeroes of *f* is equal to the number of poles of *f* in the closure of the fundamental region *R*Γ.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For the congruence subgroup Γ0(*N*), the field of modular functions on X0(*N*) is generated by the functions *j*(*z*) and *j*(*Nz*).
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Modular forms can also be interpreted geometrically as sections of line bundles on modular curves or on the moduli stack of elliptic curves.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In this interpretation, the relevant line bundle is the Hodge bundle, often denoted ω, and modular forms of weight *k* are sections of ω⊗*k* with the appropriate holomorphy condition at the cusps.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] By the Kodaira–Spencer isomorphism, the square of the Hodge bundle is identified with the logarithmic canonical bundle of the modular curve, i.e., the canonical bundle twisted with the cuspidal divisor.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The intuition is that, for a modular form *f* of weight two, the one-form f(z)dz is invariant under the action of the modular group.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] At the cusps this gives a logarithmic differential, while cusp forms give holomorphic differentials.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The dimensions of spaces of modular forms can be computed using the Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] This interpretation is analogous to the role of homogeneous polynomials on projective space.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Such polynomials are not ordinary functions on projective space, because they change by a scalar factor when the underlying vector is rescaled.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Geometrically, they are interpreted as sections of line bundles.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Modular forms behave similarly: except in weight zero, their transformation law prevents them from being ordinary functions on a modular curve, but allows them to be interpreted as sections of powers of the Hodge bundle.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For a subgroup Γ of the SL(2, **Z**), the ring of modular forms is the graded ring generated by the modular forms of Γ.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In other words, if Mk(Γ) is the vector space of modular forms of weight k, then the ring of modular forms of Γ is the graded ring $M(\Gamma )=\bigoplus _{k>0}M_{k}(\Gamma )$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Rings of modular forms of congruence subgroups of SL(2, **Z**) are finitely generated due to a result of Pierre Deligne and Michael Rapoport.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Such rings of modular forms are generated in weight at most 6 and the relations are generated in weight at most 12 when the congruence subgroup has nonzero odd weight modular forms, and the corresponding bounds are 5 and 10 when there are no nonzero odd weight modular forms.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] More generally, there are formulas for bounds on the weights of generators of the ring of modular forms and its relations for arbitrary Fuchsian groups.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] New forms are a subspace of modular forms of a fixed level N which cannot be constructed from modular forms of lower levels M dividing N .
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The other forms are called **old forms**.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] These old forms can be constructed using the following observations: if $M\mid N$ then $\Gamma _{1}(N)\subseteq \Gamma _{1}(M)$ giving a reverse inclusion of modular forms $M_{k}(\Gamma _{1}(M))\subseteq M_{k}(\Gamma _{1}(N))$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] A cusp form is a modular form that vanishes at all cusps.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] For the full modular group, which has one cusp, this is equivalent to saying that the constant coefficient in its Fourier series is zero.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] There are a number of other usages of the term "modular function", apart from this classical one; for example, in the theory of Haar measures, it is a function Δ(*g*) determined by the conjugation action.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Maass forms are real-analytic eigenfunctions of the Laplacian but need not be holomorphic.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The holomorphic parts of certain weak Maass wave forms turn out to be essentially Ramanujan's mock theta functions.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Groups which are not subgroups of SL(2, **Z**) can be considered.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Hilbert modular forms are functions in *n* variables, each a complex number in the upper half-plane, satisfying a modular relation for 2×2 matrices with entries in a totally real number field.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Jacobi forms are a mixture of modular forms and elliptic functions.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Examples of such functions are very classical - the Jacobi theta functions and the Fourier coefficients of Siegel modular forms of genus two - but it is a relatively recent observation that the Jacobi forms have an arithmetic theory very analogous to the usual theory of modular forms.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Automorphic forms extend the notion of modular forms to general Lie groups.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Modular integrals of weight k are meromorphic functions on the upper half plane of moderate growth at infinity which *fail to be modular of weight k* by a rational function.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] The function $\varepsilon (a,b,c,d)$ is called the nebentypus of the modular form.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Functions such as the Dedekind eta function, a modular form of weight 1/2, may be encompassed by the theory by allowing automorphic factors.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Yutaka Taniyama and Goro Shimura identified a 1-to-1 matching between certain modular forms and elliptic curves.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] Robert Langlands built on this idea in the construction of his expansive Langlands program, which has become one of the most far-reaching and consequential research programs in math.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In 1994 Andrew Wiles used modular forms to prove Fermat’s Last Theorem.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In 2001 all elliptic curves were proven to be modular over the rational numbers.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In 2013 elliptic curves were proven to be modular over real quadratic fields.
[src:modular-forms/modular-form] In 2023 elliptic curves were proven to be modular over about half of imaginary quadratic fields, including fields formed by combining the rational numbers with the square root of integers down to −5.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] In mathematics, the **modular group** is the projective special linear group $\operatorname {PSL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ of $2\times 2$ matrices with integer coefficients and determinant 1 , such that the matrices A and $-A$ are identified.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The modular group acts on the upper-half of the complex plane by linear fractional transformations.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The name "modular group" comes from the relation to moduli spaces, and not from modular arithmetic.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] where $a,b,c,d$ are integers, and $ad-bc=1$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The group operation is function composition.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] This group of transformations is isomorphic to the projective special linear group $\operatorname {PSL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ , which is the quotient of the 2-dimensional special linear group $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ by its center $\{I,-I\}$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] where $a,b,c,d$ are integers, $ad-bc=1$ , and pairs of matrices A and $-A$ are considered to be identical.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The group operation is usual matrix multiplication.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Some authors *define* the modular group to be $\operatorname {PSL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ , and still others define the modular group to be the larger group $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Some mathematical relations require the consideration of the group $\operatorname {GL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ of matrices with determinant plus or minus one.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] ( $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ is a subgroup of this group.) Similarly, $\operatorname {PGL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ is the quotient group $\operatorname {GL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )/\{I,-I\}$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Since all $2\times 2$ matrices with determinant 1 are symplectic matrices, then $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )=\operatorname {Sp} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ , the symplectic group of $2\times 2$ matrices.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] in $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ , begin with two coprime integers $a,b$ , and solve the determinant equation $ay-bx=1$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] is a matrix in $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Then, using the projection, these matrices define elements in $\operatorname {PSL} (2,\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] implies that the fractions ⁠*a*/*b*⁠, ⁠*a*/*c*⁠, ⁠*c*/*d*⁠, ⁠*b*/*d*⁠ are all irreducible, that is having no common factors (provided the denominators are non-zero, of course).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] is also irreducible (again, provided the denominator be non-zero).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Elements of the modular group provide a symmetry on the two-dimensional lattice.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Let *ω*1 and *ω*2 be two complex numbers whose ratio is not real.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] is a lattice of parallelograms on the plane.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] It is for this reason that doubly periodic functions, such as elliptic functions, possess a modular group symmetry.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The action of the modular group on the rational numbers can most easily be understood by envisioning a square grid, with grid point (*p*, *q*) corresponding to the fraction ⁠*p*/*q*⁠ (see Euclid's orchard).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] An irreducible fraction is one that is *visible* from the origin; the action of the modular group on a fraction never takes a *visible* (irreducible) to a *hidden* (reducible) one, and vice versa.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] In particular, if *bc* − *ad* = 1 for positive integers *a*, *b*, *c*, *d* with *a* < *b* and *c* < *d* then ⁠*a*/*b*⁠ and ⁠*c*/*d*⁠ will be neighbours in the Farey sequence of order max(*b*, *d*).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Important special cases of continued fraction convergents include the Fibonacci numbers and solutions to Pell's equation.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] In both cases, the numbers can be arranged to form a semigroup subset of the modular group.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] so that every element in the modular group can be represented (in a non-unique way) by the composition of powers of *S* and *T*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Geometrically, *S* represents inversion in the unit circle followed by reflection with respect to the imaginary axis, while *T* represents a unit translation to the right.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The generators *S* and *T* obey the relations *S*2 = 1 and (*ST*)3 = 1.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] This presentation describes the modular group as the rotational triangle group D(2, 3, ∞) (infinity as there is no relation on *T*), and it thus maps onto all triangle groups (2, 3, *n*) by adding the relation *Tn* = 1, which occurs for instance in the congruence subgroup Γ(*n*).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The braid group *B*3 is the universal central extension of the modular group, with these sitting as lattices inside the (topological) universal covering group SL2(**R**) → PSL2(**R**).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Further, the modular group has a trivial center, and thus the modular group is isomorphic to the quotient group of *B*3 modulo its center; equivalently, to the group of inner automorphisms of *B*3.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The braid group *B*3 in turn is isomorphic to the knot group of the trefoil knot.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The quotients by congruence subgroups are of significant interest.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Other important quotients are the (2, 3, *n*) triangle groups, which correspond geometrically to descending to a cylinder, quotienting the *x* coordinate modulo *n*, as *Tn* = (*z* ↦ *z* + *n*).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] (2, 3, 5) is the group of icosahedral symmetry, and the (2, 3, 7) triangle group (and associated tiling) is the cover for all Hurwitz surfaces.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The projection ${\text{SL}}_{2}(\mathbb {Z} )\to {\text{PSL}}_{2}(\mathbb {Z} )$ turns these matrices into generators of ${\text{PSL}}_{2}(\mathbb {Z} )$ , with relations similar to the group presentation.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The modular group is important because it forms a subgroup of the group of isometries of the hyperbolic plane.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Since PSL(2, **Z**) is a subgroup of PSL(2, **R**), the modular group is a subgroup of the group of orientation-preserving isometries of **H**.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The modular group Γ acts on ${\textstyle \mathbb {H} }$ as a discrete subgroup of ${\textstyle \operatorname {PSL} (2,\mathbb {R} )}$ , that is, for each *z* in ${\textstyle \mathbb {H} }$ we can find a neighbourhood of *z* which does not contain any other element of the orbit of *z*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] This also means that we can construct fundamental domains, which (roughly) contain exactly one representative from the orbit of every *z* in **H**.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] It has vertices at ⁠1/2⁠ + *i*⁠√3/2⁠ and −⁠1/2⁠ + *i*⁠√3/2⁠, where the angle between its sides is ⁠π/3⁠, and a third vertex at infinity, where the angle between its sides is 0.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] There is a strong connection between the modular group and elliptic curves.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Each point z in the upper half-plane gives an elliptic curve, namely the quotient of $\mathbb {C}$ by the lattice generated by 1 and z .
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Two points in the upper half-plane give isomorphic elliptic curves if and only if they are related by a transformation in the modular group.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Thus, the quotient of the upper half-plane by the action of the modular group is the so-called moduli space of elliptic curves: a space whose points describe isomorphism classes of elliptic curves.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] This is often visualized as the fundamental domain described above, with some points on its boundary identified.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The modular group and its subgroups are also a source of interesting tilings of the hyperbolic plane.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] By transforming this fundamental domain in turn by each of the elements of the modular group, a regular tessellation of the hyperbolic plane by congruent hyperbolic triangles known as the V6.6.∞ Infinite-order triangular tiling is created.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Note that each such triangle has one vertex either at infinity or on the real axis Im(*z*) = 0.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] This tiling can be extended to the Poincaré disk, where every hyperbolic triangle has one vertex on the boundary of the disk.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The tiling of the Poincaré disk is given in a natural way by the *J*-invariant, which is invariant under the modular group, and attains every complex number once in each triangle of these regions.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] This tessellation can be refined slightly, dividing each region into two halves (conventionally colored black and white), by adding an orientation-reversing map; the colors then correspond to orientation of the domain.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Adding in (*x*, *y*) ↦ (−*x*, *y*) and taking the right half of the region *R* (where Re(*z*) ≥ 0) yields the usual tessellation.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] This tessellation first appears in print in (Klein & 1878/79a), where it is credited to Richard Dedekind, in reference to (Dedekind 1877).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The map of groups (2, 3, ∞) → (2, 3, *n*) (from modular group to triangle group) can be visualized in terms of this tiling (yielding a tiling on the modular curve), as depicted in the video at right.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Important subgroups of the modular group Γ, called *congruence subgroups*, are given by imposing congruence relations on the associated matrices.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] There is a natural homomorphism SL(2, **Z**) → SL(2, **Z**/*N***Z**) given by reducing the entries modulo *N*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The kernel of this homomorphism is called the **principal congruence subgroup of level *N***, denoted Γ(*N*).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Being the kernel of a homomorphism Γ(*N*) is a normal subgroup of the modular group Γ.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] It is easy to show that the trace of a matrix representing an element of Γ(*N*) cannot be −1, 0, or 1, so these subgroups are torsion-free groups.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The principal congruence subgroup of level 2, Γ(2), is also called the **modular group Λ**.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Since PSL(2, **Z**/2**Z**) is isomorphic to *S*3, Λ is a subgroup of index 6.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The group Λ consists of all modular transformations for which *a* and *d* are odd and *b* and *c* are even.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Another important family of congruence subgroups are the modular groups Γ0(*N*) defined as the set of all modular transformations for which *c* ≡ 0 (mod *N*), or equivalently, as the subgroup whose matrices become upper triangular upon reduction modulo *N*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] Note that Γ(*N*) is a subgroup of Γ0(*N*).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The modular curves associated with these groups are an aspect of monstrous moonshine – for a prime number *p*, the modular curve of the normalizer is genus zero if and only if *p* divides the order of the monster group, or equivalently, if *p* is a supersingular prime.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] One important subset of the modular group is the **dyadic monoid**, which is the monoid of all strings of the form *STn1STn2STn3*... for positive integers *ni*.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] This monoid occurs naturally in the study of fractal curves, and describes the self-similarity symmetries of the Cantor function, Minkowski's question mark function, and the Koch snowflake, each being a special case of the general de Rham curve.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The monoid also has higher-dimensional linear representations; for example, the *N* = 3 representation can be understood to describe the self-symmetry of the blancmange curve.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The algebraic properties of a matrix as an element of GL(2, **Z**) correspond to the dynamics of the induced map of the torus.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The modular group can be generalized to the **Hecke groups**, named for Erich Hecke, and defined as follows.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] which corresponds to the triangle group (2, *q*, ∞).
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] There is similarly a notion of principal congruence subgroups associated to principal ideals in **Z**[*λ*].
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] The modular group and its subgroups were first studied in detail by Richard Dedekind and by Felix Klein as part of his Erlangen programme in the 1870s.
[src:modular-forms/modular-group] However, the closely related elliptic functions were studied by Joseph Louis Lagrange in 1785, and further results on elliptic functions were published by Carl Gustav Jakob Jacobi and Niels Henrik Abel in 1827.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] In number theory, the **modularity theorem** states that elliptic curves over the field of rational numbers are related to modular forms in a particular way.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Andrew Wiles and Richard Taylor proved the modularity theorem for semistable elliptic curves, which was enough to imply Fermat's Last Theorem (FLT).
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Later, a series of papers by Wiles's former students Brian Conrad, Fred Diamond and Richard Taylor, culminating in a joint paper with Christophe Breuil, extended Wiles's techniques to prove the full modularity theorem in 2001.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Before that, the statement was known as the **Taniyama–Shimura conjecture**, **Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture**, or the **modularity conjecture for elliptic curves**.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The theorem states that any elliptic curve over $\mathbb {Q}$ can be obtained via a rational map with integer coefficients from the classical modular curve *X*0(*N*) for some integer N; this is a curve with integer coefficients with an explicit definition.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] This mapping is called a modular parametrization of level N.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] To each elliptic curve E over $\mathbb {Q}$ we may attach a corresponding L-series.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] we see that we have written the Fourier expansion of a function *f*(*E*,*τ*) of the complex variable τ, so the coefficients of the q-series are also thought of as the Fourier coefficients of f.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The function obtained in this way is, remarkably, a cusp form of weight two and level N and is also an eigenform (an eigenvector of all Hecke operators); this is the **Hasse–Weil conjecture**, which follows from the modularity theorem.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Some modular forms of weight two, in turn, correspond to holomorphic differentials for an elliptic curve.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The Jacobian of the modular curve can (up to isogeny) be written as a product of irreducible Abelian varieties, corresponding to Hecke eigenforms of weight 2.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The 1-dimensional factors are elliptic curves (there can also be higher-dimensional factors, so not all Hecke eigenforms correspond to rational elliptic curves).
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The curve obtained by finding the corresponding cusp form, and then constructing a curve from it, is isogenous to the original curve (but not, in general, isomorphic to it).
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Yutaka Taniyama stated a preliminary (slightly incorrect) version of the conjecture at the 1955 international symposium on algebraic number theory in Tokyo and Nikkō as the twelfth of his set of 36 unsolved problems.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Goro Shimura and Taniyama worked on improving its rigor until 1957.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] André Weil rediscovered the conjecture, and showed in 1967 that it would follow from the (conjectured) functional equations for some twisted L-series of the elliptic curve; this was the first serious evidence that the conjecture might be true.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Weil also showed that the conductor of the elliptic curve should be the level of the corresponding modular form.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture became a part of the Langlands program.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The conjecture attracted considerable interest when Gerhard Frey suggested in 1986 that it implies FLT.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] He did this by attempting to show that any counterexample to FLT would imply the existence of at least one non-modular elliptic curve.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] This argument was moved closer to its goal in 1987 when Jean-Pierre Serre identified a missing link (now known as the epsilon conjecture or Ribet's theorem) in Frey's original work, followed two years later by Ken Ribet's completion of a proof of the epsilon conjecture.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Even after gaining serious attention, the Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture was seen by contemporary mathematicians as extraordinarily difficult to prove or perhaps even inaccessible to proof.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] For example, Wiles's Ph.D. supervisor John Coates states that it seemed "impossible to actually prove", and Ken Ribet considered himself "one of the vast majority of people who believed [it] was completely inaccessible".
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] With Ribet’s proof of the epsilon conjecture, Andrew Wiles saw an opportunity: Fermat’s Last Theorem was a respectable research project because it was now a corollary of the TSW conjecture.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] He had expertise in Iwasawa theory; maybe there was a path from Iwasawa theory to Taniyama–Shimura–Weil.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] In 1995, Andrew Wiles, with some help from Richard Taylor, proved the Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture for all semistable elliptic curves.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Wiles used this to prove FLT, and the full Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture was finally proved by Diamond, Conrad, Diamond & Taylor; and Breuil, Conrad, Diamond & Taylor; building on Wiles's work, they incrementally chipped away at the remaining cases until the full result was proved in 1999.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Once fully proven, the conjecture became known as the modularity theorem.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Several theorems in number theory similar to FLT follow from the modularity theorem.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] For example: no cube can be written as a sum of two coprime nth powers, *n* ≥ 3.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] In 2025, modularity was extended to over 10% of abelian surfaces by Boxer, Calegari, Gee and Pilloni.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The modularity theorem is a special case of more general conjectures due to Robert Langlands.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The Langlands program seeks to attach an automorphic form or automorphic representation (a suitable generalization of a modular form) to more general objects of arithmetic algebraic geometry, such as to every elliptic curve over a number field.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Most cases of these extended conjectures have not yet been proved.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] In 2013, Freitas, Le Hung, and Siksek proved that elliptic curves defined over real quadratic fields are modular.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] For prime numbers l not equal to 37, one can verify the property about the coefficients.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The conjecture, going back to the 1950s, was completely proven by 1999 using the ideas of Andrew Wiles, who proved it in 1994 for a large family of elliptic curves.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] There are several formulations of the conjecture.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Showing that they are equivalent was a main challenge of number theory in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The modularity of an elliptic curve E of conductor N can be expressed also by saying that there is a non-constant rational map defined over ℚ, from the modular curve *X*0(*N*) to E.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] In particular, the points of E can be parametrized by modular functions.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Another formulation depends on the comparison of Galois representations attached on the one hand to elliptic curves, and on the other hand to modular forms.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The latter formulation has been used in the proof of the conjecture.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Dealing with the level of the forms (and the connection to the conductor of the curve) is particularly delicate.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The most spectacular application of the conjecture is the proof of Fermat's Last Theorem (FLT).
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] has a solution with non-zero integers, hence a counter-example to FLT.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] Thus, the proof of the Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture for this family of elliptic curves (called Hellegouarch–Frey curves) implies FLT.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] The proof of the link between these two statements, based on an idea of Gerhard Frey (1985), is difficult and technical.
[src:modular-forms/modularity-theorem] It was established by Kenneth Ribet in 1987.
